* **Fourth player in NBA history** to record:
	+ at least 35 points and 19 assists in a game (Oscar Robertson, Tiny Archibald, Kevin Johnson).[269]

<fragment>

* First teenager to record four career triple-doubles in NBA history.[269]
* Broke Jason Kidd's Mavericks franchise record (21) of most triple-doubles with 22 in just 122 NBA games.[270]
* Most triple-doubles in a season (17) before turning 22 years old (2019–20 season). Previously held by Ben Simmons (12 in 2017–18).[269]
* Youngest player in NBA history to lead the league outright in triple-doubles (21 years, 168 days old). Previously held by Magic Johnson.[271]
* Twenty straight games with at least 20 points, 5 rebounds, and 5 assists, the most since the 1976–77 ABA–NBA merger. Previously held by Michael Jordan with 18 consecutive games.[272]
* First player since Tim Duncan to be selected to All-NBA First Team in a player's first or second season.[146]
* First player to lead his team outright in points, rebounds and assists in each of first three games of season.[273]
* Second-fewest games played to record 35 career triple-doubles (190). Previously held by Magic Johnson (204).[274]

</fragment>
<fragment>
* Third-fewest games played to reach 4,000 career points since the ABA–NBA merger (Michael Jordan, Shaquille O’Neal).[145]
* **First player in NBA history** to record:
	+ a 60-point, 20 rebound triple-double (60 points, 21 rebounds, 10 assists).[275]
	+ 250 points, 50 rebounds, and 50 assists in a five game span.[276]
	+ a 30-point triple-double (35 points, 12 rebounds, 10 assists) as a teenager.[277]
	+ two triple-doubles before the age of 20.[278]
	+ a 35-point triple-double in a game with 26 minutes or fewer played (35 points, 10 rebounds, and 11 assists in 25:30).[279]
	+ 30+ points, 10+ rebounds, and 15+ assists in a game with 30 minutes or fewer played (31 points, 12 rebounds, and 15 assists in 30:05).[280]
	+ 36+ points, 14+ rebounds, and 19+ assists in a game (regular season or playoffs).[269]
	+ multiple 30-point triple-doubles in games with 30 minutes or fewer played.[281]
	+ multiple 40-point triple-doubles before turning 21 years old.[282]

</fragment>
<fragment>
	+ a 30-point triple-double in a ten-game span (Oscar Robertson, Michael Jordan, Russell Westbrook, LeBron James).[285]
* **Youngest player in NBA history** to record:
	+ three triple-doubles.[112]
	+ 20 points, 15 rebounds, and 15 assists in a game.[269]
	+ 30 points, 10 rebounds, and 20 assists in a game (22 years, 62 days old).[269]
	+ 30 points, 20 rebounds, and 10 assists in a game (21 years, 158 days old).[269]
	+ 35 points, 10 rebounds, and 15 assists in a game (21 years, 162 days old). Previously held by Michael Jordan.[269]
	+ 35-point triple-doubles in succession, breaking Oscar Robertson's record.[286]

He was the fourth player to do so since the 1983–84 season, joining Michael Jordan, James Harden, and Russell Westbrook.[126][127] In November, Dončić was named the NBA Western Conference Player of the Week for Week 5 (November 18–24), his first NBA Player of the Week award.[128][129] On December 3, he won his first NBA Player of the Month award when he was named the NBA Western Conference Player of the Month for October and November. He became the youngest Western Conference Player of the Month winner since the league began issuing the award by conferences in the 2001–02 season.[130] In December, he was named *Sports Illustrated* 2019 Breakout of the Year.[131] On December 8, 2019, Dončić surpassed the record for the most consecutive games with at least 20 points, 5 rebounds, and 5 assists since the ABA-NBA merger in 1976.

## Personal life[edit]


Dončić can speak four languages: Slovenian, Serbian, English, and Spanish.[295] He learned Spanish after joining Real Madrid.[296]
